Question 3 Repeat the analysis of outlying values with z. Compared to x and y, how would you characterise the relationship of x and z, or y and z?

We make a first plot to take a look at the data:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x, z)) +
  geom_jitter()

Then we know to extract x > 0 and z > 0, with z < 10:

diamonds_zok <- filter(diamonds, x > 0, z > 0, z < 10)
ggplot(diamonds_zok, aes(x, z)) +
  geom_bin2d() +
  geom_abline(slope = 0.6, color = "white", size = 1, alpha = 0.5)

Despite the outliers, there seems to be a positive replationship between x and z.
Now lets take a look at y and z:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(y, z)) +
  geom_jitter()

We need to extract 0 < z < 10 and 0 < y < 15:

diamonds_yz <- filter(diamonds, z > 0 & z < 10, y > 0 & y < 15)
ggplot(diamonds_yz, aes(y, z)) +
  geom_bin2d() +
  geom_abline(slope = 0.65, color = "white", size = 1, alpha = 0.5)

Question 5 What is NA & FALSE and NA | TRUE? Why? Why doesnt NA * 0 equal zero? What number times zero does not equal 0? What do you expect NA 0 to equal? Why?

NA & FALSE
## [1] FALSE
# FALSE
NA | TRUE
## [1] TRUE
# TRUE

This is because the logical expressions follow the Kleene and Priest logics, view it here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-valued_logic

NA * 0
## [1] NA
# NA
NA ^ 0
## [1] 1
# 1

The reason that NA * 0 is not equal to 0 is that x * 0 = NaN is undefined when x = Inf or x = -Inf. But anything with power to 0 is 1.

Question 1 Practice your variable creation skills by creating the following new variables: - The approximate volume of the diamond (using x, y, and z).

Assuming the volume of a diamond is approximately 2/3 of a cubic with approximately the same parameters:

diamonds_q1 <- diamonds %>% 
  mutate(vol = x * y * z *(2/3))

diamonds_q1 <- diamonds_q1 %>%

Question 3 The depth variable is just the width of the diamond (average of x and y) divided by its height (z) multiplied by 100 and round to the nearest integer. Compute the depth yourself and compare it to the existing depth variable. Summarise your findings with a plot.

Depth is calculated as height(z) divided by width (avg of x and y) times 100. There is expression mistake in the question.

diamonds_q1 <- diamonds_q1 %>% 
  mutate(depth_cal = round(z / ((x + y)/2) * 100))
head(select(diamonds_q1, depth_cal, depth))
## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##   depth_cal depth
##       <dbl> <dbl>
## 1        61  61.5
## 2        60  59.8
## 3        57  56.9
## 4        62  62.4
## 5        63  63.3
## 6        63  62.8

Make a plot: We calculate the difference between the given depth and our calculated depth_cal, then we make a plot, if the plots shows more positive values, then it means our calculation is below the original, otherwise, above.

diamonds_q1 <- diamonds_q1 %>% 
  mutate(diff = depth - depth_cal,
         seq = seq_along(carat))

Question 1 For each year in the ggplot2movies::movies data determine the percent of movies with missing budgets. Visualise the result.

movies <- ggplot2movies::movies
View(movies)

We need to create a boolean column called with_budget, so if the movie has a budget, we place TRUE, else we place FALSE

movies1 <- movies %>% 
  mutate(with_budget = ifelse(is.na(budget), FALSE, TRUE)) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(
    hasBudget = sum(with_budget),
    total = n(),
    propNoBudget = 1 - hasBudget/total
  )
ggplot(movies1, aes(year, propNoBudget)) +
  geom_area(aes(fill = "linen")) +
  labs(fill = expression(atop("No Budget"))) +
  theme(legend.title = element_text(vjust = 0))

movies1

Question 2 How does the average length of a movie change over time? Display your answer with a plot, including some display of uncertainty.

We only need to group the data by year, and then calculate the mean of length, then use a line plot (since we have time and a continuous variable).

q2 <- movies %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(length))
q2

  geom_line()

As we can see, the average length of movies increased from 1890s to now.

Question 2 What does the following pipe do?

library(magrittr)
x <- runif(100)
x %>%
subtract(mean(.)) %>%
raise_to_power(2) %>%
mean() %>%
sqrt()

It loads the magittr package first, then assign 100 uniformly distributed random variable between 0 and 1 to x. Using this x, subtract each value by the mean of x. Then raise the value to the power of 2, then calculate the mean of the result, then square the result. As you can see, this is calculating the VARIANCE.
